-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Sept 11
-- 
-- Thu Sep 11, 2014 03:37AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Sept 11 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Sofia City Court postponed until October 21 its decision on Russia's request for the extradition of Russian-French businessman Nicolai Koblyakov, a prominent opponent of Vladimir Putin. Until then, Koblyakov, who was detained at the Sofia airport in July, will remain in Bulgaria. The court also decided to request Russian authorities to provide information whether the Russia has granted amnesty for the alleged wrongdoing Koblyakov is accused of (Trud, Presa). -- Interim Prime Minister Georgi Bliznashki called on Tsvetan Vassilev, the major shareholder of the troubled Corporate Commercial Bank (Corpbank) <6C9.BB> to return to Bulgaria. His comment was prompted by a statement by Vassilev's lawyer that his client was in Serbia's capital Belgrade and was working on a recovery plan for the Balkan country's fourth-largest lender (Trud, Standart, Presa, Sega). -- State gas monopoly Bulgargaz wants to raise gas prices by 1.59 percent as of Oct. 1 instead of initially planned 1.71 percent, the company said (Sega, Monitor). -- Bulgaria is struggling to meet all conditions set by European governing body UEFA for hosting a Euro 2020 game, a UEFA report showed. Germany-based company IFS plans to spend 50 million euros(64.57 million US dollar) on a new 33,000-capacity stadium in Sofia (Meridian Match, Standart).